05145nam a2200733Ia 9781501714641DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017146417 a10.1515/97815017146412doi  a(DE-B1597)496591  a(OCoLC)1020026689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a359.0309732231 aReich, Simon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe End of Grand Strategy :bUS Maritime Operations in the Twenty-First Century /cPeter Dombrowski, Simon Reich. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Naval Operations and Grand Strategy in a New Security Environment -- t2. Comparing Grand Strategies—and Their Inherent Limitations -- t3. A Maritime Strategy of Primacy in the Persian Gulf -- t4. Playing a Follow-the-Leader Strategy on the High Seas -- t5. Pirates, Terrorists, and Formal Sponsorship -- t6. Navigating the Proliferation Security Initiative and Informal Sponsorship -- t7. Racing for the Arctic with a Strategy of Restraint -- t8. Controlling the Southern Maritime Approaches with an Isolationist Strategy -- tConclusion -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The End of Grand Strategy, Simon Reich and Peter Dombrowski challenge the common view of grand strategy as unitary. They eschew prescription of any one specific approach, chosen from a spectrum that stretches from global primacy to restraint and isolationism, in favor of describing what America’s military actually does, day to day. They argue that a series of fundamental recent changes in the global system, the inevitable jostling of bureaucratic politics, and the practical limitations of field operations combine to ensure that each presidential administration inevitably resorts to a variety of strategies. Proponents of different American grand strategies have historically focused on the pivotal role of the Navy. In response, Reich and Dombrowski examine six major maritime operations, each of which reflects one major strategy. One size does not fit all, say the authors—the attempt to impose a single overarching blueprint is no longer feasible. Reich and Dombrowski declare that grand strategy, as we know it, is dead. The End of Grand Strategy is essential reading for policymakers, military strategists, and analysts and critics at advocacy groups and think tanks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSecurity Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aAmerican navy, American grand strategies, restraint and isolationism, military doctrine, military policy, naval military history.1 aDombrowski, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics and Social Sciences 2018 Englishz978311060401608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2018z9783110603231oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501714641?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501714641423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501714641/original  a978-3-11-